// Parent class
class A {
	public void show() {
		System.out.println("in A show");  // ğŸ”¹ Output when obj is instance of A
	}
}

// Child class B overriding show()
class B extends A {
	public void show() {
		System.out.println("in B show");  // ğŸ”¹ Output when obj refers to B
	}
}

// Another child class C
class C extends A {
	public void show() {
		System.out.println("in C show");  // ğŸ”¹ Output when obj refers to C
	}
}

// Unrelated class (not extending A)
class D {
	// No relationship with A
}

public class Demo {
	public static void main(String[] args) {

		A obj = new A();  // âœ… Reference type = A, Object type = A
		obj.show();       // ğŸ”¸ Output: in A show

		obj = new B();    // âœ… Reference type = A, Object type = B
		obj.show();       // ğŸ”¸ Output: in B show â†’ Run-time polymorphism

		obj = new C();    // âœ… Reference type = A, Object type = C
		obj.show();       // ğŸ”¸ Output: in C show â†’ Run-time polymorphism

		// obj = new D(); // âŒ ERROR: D is not subclass of A

		// Laptop obj1 = new Laptop();         // âœ… valid if class Laptop exists
		// Computer obj1 = new Laptop();       // âœ… Run-time polymorphism if Laptop extends Computer
	}
}


ğŸ§  POLYMORPHISM â€” Interview Theory Notes
ğŸ”µ Definition:

    Polymorphism = â€œOne name, many formsâ€
    i.e., Same function or reference behaves differently depending on context

âœŒï¸ Types of Polymorphism in Java:
Type	Also Called	Based On	Example
Compile-time Polymorphism	Static Binding, Early Binding	Method Signature	Method Overloading
Run-time Polymorphism	Dynamic Binding, Late Binding	Object Type	Method Overriding
1ï¸âƒ£ Compile-time Polymorphism (Method Overloading)

class Calculator {
	public int add(int a, int b) {
		return a + b;
	}

	public int add(int a, int b, int c) {
		return a + b + c;
	}
}

ğŸŸ¢ Compiler decides which add() to call based on number/type of arguments
2ï¸âƒ£ Run-time Polymorphism (Method Overriding)

class Computer {
	public void run() {
		System.out.println("Computer running");
	}
}

class Laptop extends Computer {
	public void run() {
		System.out.println("Laptop running");
	}
}

Computer obj = new Laptop();  // Parent reference
obj.run();                    // Output: Laptop running

ğŸŸ  JVM decides at runtime which method to call based on object type
ğŸ”¥ VERY IMPORTANT INTERVIEW POINTS
ğŸ“Œ Difference Between Overloading vs Overriding
Feature	Overloading	Overriding
Happens in	Same class	Parent-child (inheritance)
Signature	Must be different	Must be same
Return type	Can be different	Should be same or covariant
Access modifier	Can be anything	Cannot reduce visibility
Static methods	Can be overloaded	Cannot be overridden
âš ï¸ Static Binding vs Dynamic Binding
Binding Type	When decided	Example
Static	Compile-time	Overloading
Dynamic	Run-time	Overriding
ğŸ“ Summary to Remember
Concept	Key Line
Polymorphism	One interface â†’ many behaviors
Overloading	Same method name, different args
Overriding	Same method, different class
Dynamic Binding	Object type determines behavior
ğŸ’¡ Analogy to Understand

    Remote is the reference type (A)

    TV, AC, Fan are object types (B, Câ€¦)

    Depending on which device is connected, pressing â€œPowerâ€ does different behavior = Polymorphism

